'''Starcom Systems''' Inc. is a company based in Jersey, Channel Islands, specializing in wireless systems for [[Tracking system|remote tracking]], monitoring and protection of a variety of assets. Among the company's products are tracking and [[Security alarm|security systems]] for vehicles, shipping containers, merchandise and people. Its two main products are the Helios system, used for location and monitoring of vehicles, and the award-winning Watchlock padlock, which also functions as a digital security system.

==History==
The company was founded in 2004, focusing on [[Global Positioning System|vehicle tracking]] for insurance purposes. In 2005, the company introduced a vehicle location and [[fleet management system]] which was a predecessor for its later flagship product, Helios. In 2005, the company has opened its regional sales office in Argentina, followed by an office Kenya in 2008. The Helios was released to the market in 2008, followed by other tracking systems for a variety of purposes in 2012.
In 2013, Starcom Systems raised £2.7 million on London's [[Alternative Investment Market]].<ref>[http://www.globes.co.il/en/article-1000826969 "Starcom IPO raises £2.7m on London's AIM"], Globes, December 7, 2010</ref> The company's total sales in 2013 amounted to $9 million.<ref>[http://www.londonstockexchange.com/exchange/news/market-news/market-news-detail.html?announcementId=11911705 "Starcom PLC"], London Stock Exchange, April 2, 2014</ref> In 2014, the company announced that it has to defer the recognition of revenues on orders due to the effects the Crimea crisis has had on a distributor in Ukraine.<ref>[http://www.sharecast.com/news/crimea-crisis-hits-starcom/21558056.html "Crimea crisis hits Starcom"], ShareCast, March 21, 2014</ref>

==Products==
Starcom Systems manufactures several systems for different tracking purposes, each designated for a specific kind of asset.
*Helios - an automatic vehicle location and fleet management system.<ref>[http://cybertracekenya.wowcity.com/ "Track and Trace (Helios Basic and Advanced)"]</ref>
*Watchlock – a [[padlock|security padlock]] integrated with a monitoring system that provides both location information and periodical reports.<ref>[http://israel21c.org/technology/a-lock-that-keeps-an-eye-on-valuables/ "A lock that keeps an eye on valuables"], Israel21C, May 28, 2012</ref>
*Tetis – a [[shipping container|container]] tracking system based on wireless sensors within the container.<ref>[http://www.simanalytics.com/latest-in-disturbance-free-logistics/ "Latest in disturbance free logistics"], SimAnalytics, Nov. 29, 2013</ref>
*Kylos – a tracking device for merchandise and personal goods as baggage, with a built-in battery and no need for an external power supply.<ref>[http://www.proactiveinvestors.co.uk/companies/rns/130930star1938p/ "Starcom PLC"], Proactive Investors United Kingdom, Sep. 30, 2013</ref>
*Rainbow - a personal tracking device, designed for the remote monitoring of individuals at a certain level of risk – old people or young children.<ref>[http://www.gpsplus.rs/eng/products_pl500.asp "Rainbow"], GPS Plus</ref>

==Recognition==
WatchLock has won the “Physical Security Product of the Year” award at the [[IFSEC]] International 2012, Security Industry Awards event.<ref>[http://www.ifsec.co.uk/page.cfm/action=press/libID=1/libEntryID=321 "Winners gain top accolades at the IFSEC International Security Industry Awards 2012"], IFSEC International, May 16, 2012</ref>

